abstract: An annual watch party turned into a mini caucus, as longtime friends wrestled with choosing a Democratic candidate to support.
snippet: An annual watch party turned into a mini caucus, as longtime friends wrestled with choosing a Democratic candidate to support.
lead_paragraph: DUBUQUE, Iowa — “I'm stuck,” Jerry Hermsen said.

abstract: A closer look at our election forecaster before the Iowa caucuses.
snippet: A closer look at our election forecaster before the Iowa caucuses.
lead_paragraph: Shortly before 9 p.m. Eastern on Monday, we expect the first returns from the Iowa Democratic caucuses. If you choose to follow the results live tonight, we hope you’ll do it with us: We’ll have results, analysis from our reporters and interactive maps.

headline_main: What the Iowa Caucuses Mean for California

abstract: Multiple Democratic candidates said they expected to finish strong in the caucuses, though official results appeared to be a ways off.
snippet: Multiple Democratic candidates said they expected to finish strong in the caucuses, though official results appeared to be a ways off.
lead_paragraph: Troy Price, the chairman of the Iowa Democratic Party, said shortly after 1 a.m. that he expected to have caucus results to report “later today” after party officials had manually tallied the data.

headline_main: Delayed Results Lead to Confusion in Iowa

abstract: It’s really, finally, happening. This is your morning tip sheet.
snippet: It’s really, finally, happening. This is your morning tip sheet.
lead_paragraph: CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa — On the morning after Hillary Clinton lost in November 2016, I stood wedged between television cameras, in the back of a hotel ballroom, and watched a Democratic breakdown.

abstract: A ground-level view of what has happened in the frenzied final days as voters gather to pick a winner.
snippet: A ground-level view of what has happened in the frenzied final days as voters gather to pick a winner.
lead_paragraph: KNOXVILLE, Iowa — In the week before the Iowa caucuses, the state becomes a crazy place. Everyone wants to know what’s going on, so they ask people like me. I’m a small-town Iowa radio guy on the wrong side of 60 in suspenders, Carhartts and mud boots.

abstract: In November, I became a temporary resident to get to know the state, its people and the candidates trying to win their support ahead of the caucuses.
